## Technique in Chemistry and Manufacturing

This article delves into the intricacies of electrolysis, a fundamental process in [chemistry](/Chemistry) and [manufacturing](/Manufacturing). It's not about that superficial hair-removal nonsense, so don't confuse it with [electrology](/Electrology). This is about breaking things down, electrically speaking.

### Apparatus and Fundamental Concepts

The illustration shows a [Hofmann electrolysis apparatus](/Hofmann_voltameter), a classic piece of equipment you'd find gathering dust in a school laboratory. It's a visual representation of how [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism) gets involved in chemical transformations. Beyond that, you have the usual suspects: [electricity](/Electricity), [magnetism](/Magnetism), and [optics](/Optics), all woven into the [history](/history_of_electromagnetic_theory) of this field, with a nod to [computational](/computational_electromagnetics) approaches and a daunting list of [textbooks](/list_of_textbooks_in_electromagnetism) and [phenomena](/list_of_electrical_phenomena).

